All right.

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:49.439
So at the end of the talk today, hopefully you will now have some steps that you can

00:00:49.439 --> 00:00:52.599
follow to validate your R packages.

00:00:52.599 --> 00:00:57.980
So before we get going, what is computer system validation?

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:02.779
So that is establishing documentary evidence that our software performs some sort of task,

00:01:02.779 --> 00:01:07.059
activity, process, in compliance with the specification we've laid out with a high

00:01:07.059 --> 00:01:08.059
degree of assurance.

00:01:08.059 --> 00:01:10.660
So there's a couple of very important aspects to that.

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:12.699
It's documenting the evidence.

00:01:12.699 --> 00:01:16.300
And then it's compliance with the specifications with a high degree of assurance.

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:21.620
So you are sure that it will continue to behave the way you expect it to.

00:01:21.620 --> 00:01:25.900
So part of the reason that we do validation is it's required for FDA submission.

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:29.459
There's the 21 CFR 11.

00:01:29.459 --> 00:01:32.900
And there's also some general principles of software validation that was released by the

00:01:32.900 --> 00:01:37.820
FDA in 2002, giving us some guidelines about how we should be performing our validations.

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:40.379
But that isn't the only reason we should be doing validation.

00:01:40.379 --> 00:01:43.580
Validation has a lot of other benefits as well, such as improved quality and safety

00:01:43.580 --> 00:01:45.260
with the products that we generate.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:48.860
It results in faster processing, because we already have a system in place.

00:01:48.860 --> 00:01:53.959
And it promotes trust with our outputs, because we've already tested it in a variety of inputs.

00:01:53.959 --> 00:02:00.279
So we already know that it's going to produce good results, or it'll error out if it doesn't.

00:02:00.279 --> 00:02:02.120
Validation is very different from verification.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:03.120
And often, they're confused.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:05.540
So we're going to go over that a little bit too.

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:10.080
So validation is, does the system behave as we expect it to?

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:12.199
Will it return the correct value given the input?

00:02:12.199 --> 00:02:16.360
Or will it throw an error if the values are outside of our expectations?

00:02:16.360 --> 00:02:21.160
Verification on the other hand is simply do two separate processes on the same data set,

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:23.520
for example, give us the same output.

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:25.360
So it's similar, but different.

00:02:25.360 --> 00:02:28.539
And so that'll frame what we're talking about today.

00:02:28.539 --> 00:02:31.600
But for small companies, validation can be a high bar.

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:34.380
There's a lot of labor hours in validation.

00:02:34.380 --> 00:02:36.119
And there's tracking the progress.

00:02:36.119 --> 00:02:41.960
There's writing everything around that, and tracking the documentation, which can feel

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:43.199
like a lot of work.

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:47.800
You're constantly filling out this paperwork that's outside of your coding.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.399
For validation, it feels a little excessive, because you first have to develop and get

00:02:51.399 --> 00:02:52.399
sign-off on your specifications.

00:02:52.399 --> 00:02:56.960
Next, you're going to have to write the actual code following good programming practices

00:02:56.960 --> 00:02:59.880
and record who wrote which functions.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:03.679
Then you have to document and develop your test cases and get sign-off on that.

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:08.520
Next, write your test code based on your test cases and record who wrote that.

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:11.559
Manually evaluate and document the test code results.

00:03:11.559 --> 00:03:13.679
Once again, getting a third party to do that.

00:03:13.679 --> 00:03:18.039
And finally, review all this documentation that you have and get final sign-off for release.

00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:19.039
That's a lot of work.

00:03:19.039 --> 00:03:22.000
It's a lot of different parts of validation.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.440
And at any point, it can feel like game over.

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:29.360
You just have to restart and redo the whole process over again.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:33.360
But I'm here to tell you that validation and R can be best friends.

00:03:33.360 --> 00:03:37.080
They can work together to create an awesome product.

00:03:37.080 --> 00:03:42.240
Using R Markdown, test that, and Roxygen 2, we can create PDFs that look like this within

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:49.800
our packages that track who wrote the specifications, who wrote the functions, who wrote the test

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.639
cases and test code.

00:03:51.639 --> 00:03:56.199
Capture our specifications as we wrote them and the test cases within the PDF and finally

00:03:56.199 --> 00:04:00.160
display all the test results surrounding them.

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:01.160
So my name is Ellis Hughes.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:02.639
I'm a statistical programmer.

00:04:02.639 --> 00:04:07.399
I have a history working in statistical genetics, and currently I work in HIV vaccine research.

00:04:07.399 --> 00:04:09.119
I'm also really involved with the community.

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:11.720
I'm a Seattle Use R organizer.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:16.679
And this past year I helped run the Cascadia R conference, which was really rewarding.

00:04:16.679 --> 00:04:21.279
Fred Hutch is known for cancer research, but they also do vaccine development.

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:23.399
And that's the group that I work within.

00:04:23.399 --> 00:04:24.399
It's called SHARP.

00:04:24.399 --> 00:04:29.519
We were established in 1992, and we've had a worldwide impact on HIV and AIDS vaccine

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:31.519
research.

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:35.160
So here's the five steps that I would say are part of validation.

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:37.839
First you have to have your specifications.

00:04:37.839 --> 00:04:39.200
Then you write the code.

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.799
Then you write your test cases.

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:42.519
Then you write the actual test case code.

00:04:42.519 --> 00:04:44.239
And finally you document it all together.

00:04:44.239 --> 00:04:48.040
I'm also assuming that you're going to be writing a package for this validation.

00:04:48.040 --> 00:04:53.760
So here's a sample of what a generic package might look like.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:58.959
So first, when you're working on your specifications, you're trying to lay out what are the requirements

00:04:58.959 --> 00:05:00.079
of your package.

00:05:00.079 --> 00:05:01.399
What will the package do?

00:05:01.399 --> 00:05:04.320
What are the expected outputs of your package?

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:06.640
And what are the high-level steps that are going to be followed?

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:07.920
So this isn't going into detail.

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:11.160
This is laying out the groundwork for everything.

00:05:11.160 --> 00:05:15.239
So if I were to be writing a specification for my presentation today, I'd say the contents

00:05:15.239 --> 00:05:19.279
of my presentation will cover my team's approach to validation.

00:05:19.279 --> 00:05:24.200
It'll be roughly 15 to 20 minutes long, and hopefully it'll be entertaining.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:30.559
So when I go to record these specifications, I'm going to want to use R Markdown to document

00:05:30.559 --> 00:05:31.559
all this for me.

00:05:31.559 --> 00:05:36.959
I'm going to use a single file per specification and number those specifications within it.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:43.000
In addition, I'm going to use Roxygen2 to add details around who wrote that specification

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.880
and when, and what the specification title is, and then I'm going to put this inside

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:48.399
my R package.

00:05:48.399 --> 00:05:53.279
So these are the same specifications that I had earlier, but now it's written in Markdown.

00:05:53.279 --> 00:06:00.320
I have details surrounding what the specification is, and that I wrote it, and I wrote it yesterday.

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:05.440
I also will explain what the validation procedure, be 15 to 20 minutes long, and hopefully be

00:06:05.440 --> 00:06:06.440
entertaining.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:09.239
Fame and glamour might follow later, who knows.

00:06:09.239 --> 00:06:14.160
So the benefit of putting our specifications within our package and writing it in R Markdown,

00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:18.359
it allows us to really quickly update the specifications if any of them change.

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:20.079
Additionally, we can change the ownership.

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:25.959
If somebody goes and updates the specifications, they are already right there for them to update.

00:06:25.959 --> 00:06:29.600
By putting it inside the package, it's close to the task at hand, so it's really easy to

00:06:29.600 --> 00:06:30.600
reference.

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:33.880
You don't have to find a third-party document to pull that information in.

00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:38.320
But also by separating out the specifications in their own files, it forces you to decouple

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:42.920
your specifications so they're not reliant on one another, so you can make very clear

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:45.440
specifications.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:47.720
These specifications are Markdown files.

00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:51.480
We suggest putting them under the vignettes folder, creating a validation folder, and

00:06:51.480 --> 00:06:56.320
finally creating a folder for all your specifications and dropping all of them in there.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:57.320
Now your code.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:00.239
Now, you might be thinking this right now.

00:07:00.239 --> 00:07:03.200
And don't worry, I'm not here to tell you actually how to code.

00:07:03.519 --> 00:07:06.559
I'm simply going to talk about how you want to document this code when you're writing

00:07:06.559 --> 00:07:08.359
it for validation.

00:07:08.359 --> 00:07:12.079
So typically, when you're documenting the code ownership, you're going to be using an

00:07:12.079 --> 00:07:16.480
external resource, such as Word, Excel, maybe Smartsheets, and this is really cumbersome

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:19.040
because it's outside of your programming world.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:23.279
You have to take a minute and step out of it and go and record, oh, I updated this function

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:25.920
on this date, and here's what happened.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:29.679
And that really just takes you out of their flow of programming.

00:07:29.679 --> 00:07:35.399
What I suggest doing is using the section tag in Roxygen and documenting the last updated

00:07:35.399 --> 00:07:38.480
by and the last updated date.

00:07:38.480 --> 00:07:42.399
So you can record who updated it and when, and it's right there within the function.

00:07:42.399 --> 00:07:46.079
You can also do it at function creation.

00:07:46.079 --> 00:07:49.760
The benefit of using these Roxygen tags is it doesn't alter how it would behave when

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:53.799
you're trying to compile your manuals, and it actually has the added benefit of recording

00:07:53.799 --> 00:07:57.799
it in the manual who wrote the function and when they last updated it, so you can track

00:07:57.799 --> 00:07:58.799
that.

00:07:58.799 --> 00:08:01.559
But now somebody came in and they updated my function.

00:08:01.559 --> 00:08:04.959
They changed how long the function is going to wait.

00:08:04.959 --> 00:08:09.239
And so this was not done by me, and it was done today.

00:08:09.239 --> 00:08:10.959
But it is right there in the code.

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:14.720
They didn't have to step outside and remember to update it in the Smartsheet or the Excel

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:19.959
file, but it's able to do it right there within the function and in the commit, it's tracked

00:08:19.959 --> 00:08:22.079
if you're using version control.

00:08:22.079 --> 00:08:25.839
So when you compile it and build your functions, it doesn't look any different.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:27.079
You can write your tests as well.

00:08:27.079 --> 00:08:30.839
It's going to behave exactly the same as it normally would, but now you have this tracker

00:08:30.839 --> 00:08:33.640
embedded into your code.

00:08:33.640 --> 00:08:36.280
Now when you're writing your test cases, so test cases are where you're actually going

00:08:36.280 --> 00:08:40.880
to draw the connection between the code that you wrote and the actual specifications that

00:08:40.880 --> 00:08:43.880
you have and how to pair them together.

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:45.200
These are distinct from unit tests.

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:50.760
They're often confused with one another, but unit tests are for testing as the function

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:55.119
author does your function behave the way you're expecting it to.

00:08:55.119 --> 00:09:00.760
Test cases, on the other hand, are for documenting how you've matched up with your specifications.

00:09:00.760 --> 00:09:01.760
Similar but different.

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:09.640
A single test case can satisfy multiple specifications, conversely, a single specification must match

00:09:09.640 --> 00:09:14.200
to at least one test case, so you have to prove that each specification has been met.

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:18.479
So the way you go through and document your test cases is first you record which specification

00:09:18.479 --> 00:09:23.520
is going to be met, specify the required input data for your test case, record the steps

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:30.039
you need to be following but without writing any code, then detail the expectations that

00:09:30.039 --> 00:09:34.119
they'll need to be testing to prove that you've met these specifications.

00:09:34.119 --> 00:09:39.479
You'll use R Markdown to perform this task, and you'll use Roxygen 2 to document all that

00:09:39.479 --> 00:09:43.640
additional information, such as who wrote that test case and when.

00:09:43.640 --> 00:09:45.559
So this is what a test case might look like.

00:09:45.559 --> 00:09:51.179
Once again, for my presentation, I would first see that I met my specifications by gathering

00:09:51.179 --> 00:09:57.059
a captive audience of coworkers and probably later my significant other, give them the

00:09:57.059 --> 00:10:01.419
presentation and ask them, if it was informative, ask them what they learned.

00:10:01.419 --> 00:10:06.179
I can then time my presentation to see if I was actually between the 15 and 20 minutes,

00:10:06.179 --> 00:10:10.059
and then I can see if I was entertaining by the number of eye rolls from my significant

00:10:10.059 --> 00:10:13.260
other or chuckles from my coworkers.

00:10:13.260 --> 00:10:19.580
By using this modular test case format, it makes it easy to shift and update your test

00:10:19.739 --> 00:10:23.700
cases so you can, as you get more information, you can change them or make sure that you're

00:10:23.700 --> 00:10:25.739
hitting all the specifications.

00:10:25.739 --> 00:10:29.340
These will also live under the validation folder you created, but create a new folder

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:32.700
called test cases.

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:33.979
Now test case coding.

00:10:33.979 --> 00:10:38.460
This is where you actually implement the new test cases that you just wrote in R Markdown.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:44.099
You're going to record the results of those test cases, and then you're going to have

00:10:44.099 --> 00:10:46.419
a third party write this code.

00:10:46.419 --> 00:10:50.820
It's critical to have this third party do it, because they have no prior knowledge of

00:10:50.820 --> 00:10:53.380
the way the function should be behaving.

00:10:53.380 --> 00:10:59.179
The benefits of this is it helps resolve any interpretation errors before you release it.

00:10:59.179 --> 00:11:01.859
They're able to go through your documentation, because they don't know the way that it's

00:11:01.859 --> 00:11:07.500
supposed to behave, and see if there's anything that's unclear about your arguments, the way

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:08.500
you set that up.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:12.380
Additionally, they'll be going through your test cases and seeing how that works, and

00:11:12.460 --> 00:11:17.580
if there's any ambiguity in the way that they're supposed to be processing it, they come back

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:22.059
and ask you, and they can improve your test cases, improve your code.

00:11:22.059 --> 00:11:26.659
They can also potentially identify any places for improvements in your code itself.

00:11:26.659 --> 00:11:30.659
They could have a preconceived notion with the way how quickly things should be running,

00:11:30.659 --> 00:11:34.179
and by going through it, and if it runs slower, they can bring that up to you, and you can

00:11:34.179 --> 00:11:36.739
go back and update it.

00:11:36.739 --> 00:11:40.900
The approach that we're going to take with this test code is we're going to use a familiar

00:11:40.900 --> 00:11:42.580
format called test that.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:44.739
I think most people that have developed a hack to know that.

00:11:44.739 --> 00:11:48.059
We're also going to augment these test cases with Roxygen 2.

00:11:48.059 --> 00:11:51.820
I don't know if you've noticed, but there's a bit of a theme.

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:58.539
This looks like any other test case that you might run normally, but we've added this Roxygen

00:11:58.539 --> 00:12:05.380
documentation about what the test is, who wrote that test, and when they wrote it.

00:12:05.380 --> 00:12:07.780
It was not done by me, so it's a third party.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:12.900
They did it today, and they wrote out all the expectations that they were supposed to

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:13.900
be doing.

00:12:13.900 --> 00:12:15.219
In this case, the test case was rather simple.

00:12:15.219 --> 00:12:20.179
They were just putting in a simple function and seeing what it returned, but this is a

00:12:20.179 --> 00:12:23.659
simplification of the idea that can be generally applicable.

00:12:23.659 --> 00:12:26.099
We're using test that because it's a familiar framework.

00:12:26.099 --> 00:12:29.859
Most people, if they've written a package before, already know how to write tests using

00:12:29.859 --> 00:12:30.979
test that.

00:12:30.979 --> 00:12:34.900
They can develop their test code interactively, meaning they don't have to just send it off

00:12:34.900 --> 00:12:39.780
to batch and have it run and see what the results are, but it does allow for automation,

00:12:39.780 --> 00:12:44.820
so we can actually execute all of the test cases at once within a file and capture all

00:12:44.820 --> 00:12:47.419
that information in what's called a reporter object.

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:53.140
These are objects output by test that, and they track each test and expectations.

00:12:53.140 --> 00:13:00.000
It will report a success if each expectation passes, and it'll report failure, and for

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.760
each one of the expectations you have, track all that as well.

00:13:03.760 --> 00:13:07.640
The benefit is also that we can easily access the contents.

00:13:07.640 --> 00:13:11.440
This is a standard output of a reporter object that you're probably familiar with if you're

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:17.200
building tests and do control shift T in your RStudio IDE, it'll output that, and you could

00:13:17.200 --> 00:13:21.880
do that if that's acceptable by your organization, but we were required to actually make a nice

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:26.479
printed output of a table where we're recording each of our expectations and whether they

00:13:26.479 --> 00:13:31.940
were as expected, or it'll report the failure mode, and then, additionally, a pass fail

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:33.080
surrounding that.

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:37.559
By writing our test code additionally in this modular format, it makes it so that we can

00:13:37.559 --> 00:13:43.919
update the test code and track who updated that when independently.

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:48.840
If somebody works on a function, but they can then still do test code development for

00:13:48.840 --> 00:13:53.359
functions that they haven't worked on yet, these will live within the validation folder,

00:13:53.359 --> 00:13:58.539
as I said earlier, this time under test code, and number them from however many test cases

00:13:58.539 --> 00:13:59.539
you have.

00:13:59.539 --> 00:14:00.539
All right.

00:14:00.539 --> 00:14:04.780
So, the final document, what we're gonna be presenting at the very end is, so what do

00:14:04.780 --> 00:14:05.780
we have so far?

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:09.979
We first have the documents written in Markdown for the specifications.

00:14:09.979 --> 00:14:14.979
Next, we have Roxygen documentation and all our code that records who wrote what.

00:14:14.979 --> 00:14:18.940
We have documents in our test case, or excuse me, we have our test cases written in Markdown

00:14:18.940 --> 00:14:23.460
that we can scrape that as well, and we have our test case code that is written in TestLat

00:14:23.460 --> 00:14:28.020
augmented with Roxygen documentation, so you can use Roxygen 2 to scrape all the lists

00:14:28.020 --> 00:14:32.200
of ownership from all of our various locations.

00:14:32.200 --> 00:14:37.659
We have our Markdown, so we can pull that out of the files and print that out nicely,

00:14:37.659 --> 00:14:39.859
and we can use that to generate our final document.

00:14:39.859 --> 00:14:43.940
Finally, we have TestLat that records all the results of the code, and we can then print

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:45.580
that into a nice table.

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:50.059
So with their powers combined, we can generate that PDF that I showed you earlier, but now

00:14:50.059 --> 00:14:54.780
you have some reference, and each of the specifications and all the documents that I showed you earlier

00:14:54.780 --> 00:15:01.380
were used to compile this PDF, where I wrote the specifications, but I did not write the

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:04.140
most recent version of that function.

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:10.020
Additionally, the specifications of what my presentation must be and what I was going

00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:13.179
to be testing and the expectations at the very end are all documented there, so you

00:15:13.179 --> 00:15:18.859
can grow this as many tests as you need to to pass all your specifications.

00:15:18.859 --> 00:15:21.679
So this is what the final file format might look like.

00:15:21.679 --> 00:15:26.799
It doesn't look any different than another R package, but it has this ability to have

00:15:26.799 --> 00:15:32.400
validation stored within it and makes it very simple for you to validate, or makes the process

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:33.400
very simple.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:36.979
So validation in R can truly live together forever.

00:15:36.979 --> 00:15:41.320
So I'd like to take a second to thank my team back at Fred Hutch for helping me to work

00:15:41.320 --> 00:15:44.320
and develop this idea and this presentation.

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:48.919
Thank my wife for listening to me give this presentation a number of times.

00:15:48.919 --> 00:15:54.280
This presentation is available at thebioengineer.github.io, slash validation.

00:15:54.280 --> 00:16:01.000
The HTML behind all of the slides, as well as a sample package, lives on my GitHub, slash

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.719
validation, and then you can find me on Twitter.

00:16:03.719 --> 00:16:04.719
Thank you.

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:12.760
Awesome job, Alice.

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:16.640
We do have a couple questions here for you, and we have five minutes, so let's go ahead

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:19.760
and tackle these.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:24.679
The first one is, how does version control EG get fit into validation?

00:16:24.679 --> 00:16:30.400
Is that a viable alternative to tags inside the code itself?

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:35.400
So that depends on your org's take on version control and how they want to approach that.

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:40.559
This makes it so that we can track this outside of version control and makes it independent

00:16:40.559 --> 00:16:41.559
of any of that.

00:16:41.559 --> 00:16:46.919
So, I mean, potentially if your org would allow that, but it's all dependent on your

00:16:46.919 --> 00:16:47.919
org.

00:16:47.919 --> 00:16:48.919
Fantastic.

00:16:48.919 --> 00:16:53.000
Question two, how do these methods of validating internal packages compare and contrast with

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.559
how you validate external packages?

00:16:56.559 --> 00:17:03.039
Well, I guess that would be, once again, dependent on your org, how you want to approach that.

00:17:03.039 --> 00:17:07.040
So, I mean, eventually it would be really cool if we get all packages to start doing

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:11.040
this approach, especially if you're going to use it in pharma, where we can have this

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:15.280
document of truth going, this is what I tested, here's what I was testing against, and here's

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:16.599
what the results were.

00:17:16.599 --> 00:17:21.880
I'll also add, there's the R validation hub that's looking at that challenge.

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:27.760
The third question here is, how long, let me see, oh, here's another one.

00:17:27.760 --> 00:17:31.599
Ever looked at how CI or CD tools could fit into this workflow?

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:36.400
I definitely think there's an opportunity to use that as part of your build process,

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:40.439
where you can have it build this validation tool for you.

00:17:40.439 --> 00:17:43.760
What I didn't go into is the idea that we would then print out this PDF at the end of

00:17:43.760 --> 00:17:49.280
the day, have people manually sign off, because we don't have e-cigs yet, and we can then

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:53.560
have a final Word document that's like, this is truth.

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:59.280
We've signed off on this manually in wet ink, but it was generated automatically for us.

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:00.280
Awesome.

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:01.280
Awesome.

00:18:01.280 --> 00:18:04.000
I got two last questions here we'll tackle real quick.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:08.359
The first one, how do you document co-testing coverage?

00:18:08.359 --> 00:18:13.359
So there's several tools in R to do that in generic test cases.

00:18:13.359 --> 00:18:18.699
But with these test cases here that we're documenting, we don't necessarily have a direct

00:18:18.699 --> 00:18:19.699
way to test that.

00:18:19.699 --> 00:18:23.199
That would be definitely a good feature to be adding, is tracking which specifications

00:18:23.199 --> 00:18:26.000
are being met by which, so you can create a matrix.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
That's definitely a good idea.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:28.000
Awesome.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:29.000
Well, thank you, Ellis.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:30.000
It was a great talk.

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:31.000
Thank you.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Thank you.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.000
Thank you.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:34.000
Thank you.

